    "faq": {
      "type": "brand-faq",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_1": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "What is the difference between neutral-cure and acetoxy silicone?",
            "answer": "<p><strong>Neutral-cure silicones</strong> (like Siroflex LMN) cure without releasing acetic acid, making them almost odourless and safe for use on sensitive substrates such as PVCu, lead, natural stone and mirrors. <strong>Acetoxy silicones</strong> (like Siroflex GP) release a vinegar-like smell during curing and are best suited for glass, ceramics and non-porous surfaces. For glazing and PVCu work, always use neutral cure.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_2": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How long does Siroflex silicone take to cure?",
            "answer": "<p>Siroflex silicones typically skin over within <strong>10-20 minutes</strong> and achieve a full cure in <strong>24-48 hours</strong> depending on joint depth, temperature and humidity. Deeper joints take longer to cure. For optimal results, apply at temperatures between 5\u00b0C and 35\u00b0C and avoid exposure to water during the first 24 hours.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_3": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I paint over Siroflex sealants?",
            "answer": "<p>Siroflex <strong>acrylic caulks</strong> are instantly paintable with most water-based and synthetic paints \u2014 they are designed specifically for decorating applications. <strong>Silicone sealants cannot be painted over</strong> as paint will not adhere to silicone surfaces. If you need a paintable seal, choose an acrylic caulk or the Siroflex Polyflex HM polyurethane sealant, which is also paintable once cured.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_4": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is Siroflex expanding foam fire-rated?",
            "answer": "<p>The standard Siroflex PU Expanding Foam is classified as <strong>B3</strong> (normal combustibility). For fire-stopping applications, use <strong>Siroflex Flameguard B1</strong> fire-retardant expanding foam, which is tested to NEN6069:1997 and conforms to B1-F30 according to DIN4102-1. Always check building regulations for specific fire-stopping requirements on your project.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_5": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Which Siroflex silicone should I use for PVCu windows?",
            "answer": "<p>Use the <strong>Siroflex SX PVCu Silicone</strong> \u2014 a fast, neutral-curing silicone specifically formulated for PVCu window and door frames. Available in white, clear, light oak and bronze to match common frame colours. Neutral cure means no acid damage to the PVCu profile and an almost odourless application.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_6": {
          "type": "faq",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Do you offer trade pricing on Siroflex products?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes. We offer <strong>competitive trade pricing</strong> across the full Siroflex range including silicones, caulks, foams and adhesives. Contact our trade team on <strong>01843 593 440</strong> or email <strong>sales@invictatools.co.uk</strong> for volume discounts and trade account enquiries. We also provide free next-day delivery on all orders over \u00a399.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
